  "prompt": "What does the Bible say about Muhammad?",
  "response": "The Bible does not mention Muhammad directly, as he lived in the 6th and 7th centuries CE, long after the texts of the Bible were written. The Bible is primarily composed of texts sacred to Christianity and Judaism, while Muhammad is recognized as the final prophet in Islam, which was established in the 7th century CE.\n\nIslamic tradition holds that Muhammad is the last in a line of prophets that includes figures also recognized in the Bible, such as Moses, Abraham, and Jesus. Muslims believe that Muhammad received revelations from God (Allah) that form the Quran, which they consider the final and complete revelation.\n\nWhile the Bible does not speak of Muhammad, some Muslims interpret certain passages as prophetic or pointing toward his coming, but these interpretations are not accepted in Christian theology. In summary, the Bible does not mention Muhammad, and any connections are largely based on interpretative perspectives rather than direct references.",
